To install Node.js version 14 on Ubuntu 22.04 using NVM (Node Version Manager), you can follow these steps:

1. Update your Ubuntu system's package lists by running the following command:

   ```
   sudo apt update
   ```

2. Install NVM by running the following command:

   ```
   curl -o- https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nvm-sh/nvm/v0.39.0/install.sh | bash
   ```

   This command will download and execute the NVM installation script.

3. Close and reopen your terminal, or run the following command to load NVM:

   ```
   source ~/.bashrc
   ```

4. Verify that NVM is installed correctly by running the following command:

   ```
   nvm --version
   ```

   It should display the version of NVM installed.

5. Install Node.js version 14 using NVM:

   ```
   nvm install 14
   ```

   This command will download and install Node.js version 14.

6. Verify that Node.js version 14 is installed by running the following command:

   ```
   node --version
   ```

   It should display the version number starting with `v14`.

7. You can also set Node.js version 14 as the default version by running:

   ```
   nvm alias default 14
   ```

   This command will set Node.js version 14 as the default version that will be used when opening new terminal sessions.

That's it! You have successfully installed Node.js version 14 on Ubuntu 22.04 using NVM. You can now use Node.js 14 for your development projects.
